body:
I'm OK if it can be changed based on preferences.

And actually `arrayItem` is already implemented as not throwing an exception, so if we want to respect SQL standard, we should change that.

```
  public static Object arrayItem(List list, int item) {
    if (item < 1 || item > list.size()) {
      return null;
    }
    return list.get(item - 1);
  }
```

I'm not clear why ArrayIndexOutOfBound happened before patching.

Looking at `java.lang.ResultSet` in JDK8, `relative(int)` and `absolute(int)` both take integers. Is there a reason for this to be a `long`?

I don't see anything outwardly wrong with this change (in fact, the protobuf "Frame" message uses a `long` itself), I'm just curious about how you came about the desire to change this.

```
// A collection of rows
message Frame {
  uint64 offset = 1;
  bool done = 2;
  repeated Row rows = 3;
}
```
